workHistory.jobDescription: I was hired to enhance and maintain the lead workflow system thatsupports our agency clients in a variety of industries (education,mortgage, insurance, and health services). The primaryservice receives a message, processes business rules using a ruleengine, routes the message based on the result of those rules, and provides status information in the web response to the subscriber of the service in just a few seconds. workHistory.title: Technical Team Lead
workHistory.jobDescription:
I was hired to enhance and maintain the lead workflow system that
supports our agency clients in a variety of industries (education,
mortgage, insurance, and health services). In January 2014, I was
promoted to technical lead for this team.
  The primary lead workflow system processes tens of thousands of transactions per day from hundreds of 3rd party vendors. The primary
service receives a message, processes business rules using a rule
engine, routes the message based on the result of those rules, and provides status information in the web response to the subscriber of the service in just a few seconds. All of this is done while relying on 3rd
party services for some of the business rules which increases the
overall lead processing time - were it not for those 3rd party services,
we could process the lead in under a second every time. The


complexity of this system has grown since I began however the performance has not degraded.
  While the majority of my dev time has been spent working on web
services, database code, and BizTalk to support the system I described
previously, I have also spent a considerable amount of time building and maintaining the tools that allow the business to manage lead
delivery. This involves building reports via SSRS, creating SSIS
packages for ETL and data warehousing processes, and adding new
functionality to both a public-facing and internal web portal that can be
used to modify how the primary lead delivery system functions. Those
web portals are built with a variety of Microsoft technologies: ASP.NET
WebForms, ASP.NET MVC, Telerik UI components (for both WebForms and MVC), Entity Framework, Enterprise Library, and LINQ.
  Due to the small size of the company, individuals take on multiple roles
which are often segregated in larger organizations. My core
responsibilities in this role include: business analysis, software design,
project planning, software development / code reviews / deployment / maintenance, and managerial responsibilities for developers that
report to me.

workHistory.title: Senior .NET Developer
workHistory.jobDescription:
Initially I was hired to a small team (autonomous from IT) which was
responsible for the design, development, and management of all
operating company public-facing websites, marketing initiatives, and SEO/SEM. After this organization was merged into IT, I was promoted to a senior developer role with increased responsibilities.
  My primary focus was on public-facing websites, although I also built
and supported intranet sites, integrations between back-office systems and vendors, and other time-sensitive projects for the business. While
the demographics of the group had changed over the years, my focus
had always been on delivering quality in a very short period of time while still maintaining best practices (search engine optimization, code
scalability, standards, and reliability).
  I was the lead developer on one of our operating companies intranet
site redesigns. This project involved a migration from MCMS to SharePoint 2007. My time was spent building a scalable SharePoint
solution package for a web farm which contained multiple features to support the functionality required by the business (custom WebParts with WPF/Silverlight controls which communicated with web services
attached to a database and Active Directory).
  I was the lead developer in charge of our proprietary CMS, which had
gone through many revisions since I inherited it. Security and logging
were enhanced, web services were added to nearly every functional


area within the project to allow code reuse between the CMS, the distributed systems integrated with it, and the public-facing websites which consume the data managed through it. Preview functionality was
added for most of the features to allow the users of the CMS to see
exactly what the impact of their changes will be before they commit
them to the live environment. The project had been upgraded from
.NET 2.0 to .NET 4.1 so that the new functionality that I added for one
of our operating company site redesigns can take advantage of Entity
Framework, Code First, MVC, SqlMigrations, and unit tests.

workHistory.title: Programmer Analyst

These include desktop client/server, web-based, nightly backup, and data transfer applications that span many different languages

addition to applications developed in-house, the county acquired many
COTS and vendor products that I tested, implemented, supported, or modified to accommodate the needs of the county.
